00:21:35.320 --> 00:21:37.520
than you would think.

00:21:37.520 --> 00:21:40.000
The widgets are generally
content-rich, which it makes

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:41.170
sense for the widgets
provider.

00:21:41.170 --> 00:21:42.410
And it makes sense
to the user.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:44.580
They want to see the
beautiful images.

00:21:44.580 --> 00:21:46.500
But it uses a fair
amount of memory.

00:21:46.500 --> 00:21:48.030
And so this--

00:21:48.030 --> 00:21:50.560
just using the memory, Nova
Launcher can hit its memory,

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:53.190
or any launcher can hit its
memory limits for having too

00:21:53.190 --> 00:21:55.200
many of these widgets.

00:21:55.200 --> 00:21:59.130
Or changing out these images can
cause garbage collection,

00:21:59.130 --> 00:22:02.640
which is going to slow the
scroll of the launcher.

00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:05.190
So really, I like to see the
well designed widgets there

00:22:05.190 --> 00:22:07.350
that are just using right image
size or that are using

00:22:07.350 --> 00:22:08.440
these images.

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:10.480
They're sending them
efficiently, so there's less

00:22:10.480 --> 00:22:13.000
work on the launcher, and it
keeps everything smooth.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:13.400
RETO MEIER: All right.

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:16.870
So then basically, the better
the widget, the more smooth,

00:22:16.870 --> 00:22:19.550
fast, and efficient your
launcher can be.

00:22:19.550 --> 00:22:20.780
KEVIN BARRY: Yeah.

00:22:20.780 --> 00:22:22.025
Many users care about this.

00:22:22.025 --> 00:22:24.307
And they will start noticing
it's not the launcher, it's

00:22:24.307 --> 00:22:25.690
the widget.

00:22:25.690 --> 00:22:28.680
And they'll ask me for widget
recommendations.

00:22:28.680 --> 00:22:29.560
RETO MEIER: Nice.

00:22:29.560 --> 00:22:31.690
So that's yet another
vested interest.

00:22:31.690 --> 00:22:32.370
It's interesting.

00:22:32.370 --> 00:22:34.410
It's something we found last
year at I/O. We made a big

00:22:34.410 --> 00:22:37.690
deal about Project Butter,
making everything smoother and

00:22:37.690 --> 00:22:39.570
faster, and everything else.

00:22:39.570 --> 00:22:41.350
So it becomes incredibly
important when you're

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:43.100
embedding someone else's app--

00:22:43.100 --> 00:22:45.950
you know, their widget into
your app if you want what

00:22:45.950 --> 00:22:47.440
you're doing to be smooth
and buttery.

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:49.515
And users-- like you say--
really do care.

00:22:49.515 --> 00:22:51.305
It's important that the things
you're putting in

00:22:51.305 --> 00:22:53.140
there work as well.

00:22:53.140 --> 00:22:56.600
So what are some of the most
common best practices, or I

00:22:56.600 --> 00:22:57.850
guess maybe anti-patents--

00:22:57.850 --> 00:23:01.020
either way you want to look at
it-- that you've seen widget

00:23:01.020 --> 00:23:05.270
developers use or not use, which
you'd like to share.

00:23:05.270 --> 00:23:09.390
KEVIN BARRY: So the main thing I
wanted to talk about was how

00:23:09.390 --> 00:23:11.120
to set the images.

00:23:11.120 --> 00:23:15.940
And so, there's two popular ways
of a setting the images.

00:23:15.940 --> 00:23:17.530
One is to use the
remote views.

00:23:17.530 --> 00:23:21.220
They have a set bitmap or
set image view bitmap.

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:23.000
And this is pretty nasty.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:24.440
If you use it for a small
bitmap, it's fine.

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:26.565
And it's convenient, because you
just generate your bitmap,

00:23:26.565 --> 00:23:27.490
and you send it.

00:23:27.490 --> 00:23:30.300
But what has to happen here
is, first, your service--

00:23:30.300 --> 00:23:33.385
your widget service has to make
a copy of all the pixels

00:23:33.385 --> 00:23:34.280
of the bitmap.

00:23:34.280 --> 00:23:35.790
So it's a large amount.

00:23:35.790 --> 00:23:38.590
Then it gives it to the Android
framework, where that

00:23:38.590 --> 00:23:40.960
has to hold onto it for
a little while.

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:42.970
Then it sends it to
the launcher.

00:23:42.970 --> 00:23:45.925
The launcher then has to
unparcel that, so it's

00:23:45.925 --> 00:23:47.060
creating another copy of it.

00:23:47.060 --> 00:23:49.720
So a large amount-- double the
memory needed for the image.

00:23:49.720 --> 00:23:51.810
And then we can ultimately
display it.

00:23:51.810 --> 00:23:53.860
So this is-- it's creating
garbage.

00:23:53.860 --> 00:23:57.440
And Android has a transaction
size limit, so you

00:23:57.440 --> 00:23:59.090
individually can only
transfer so much.

00:23:59.090 --> 00:24:01.415
And I only [INAUDIBLE]
can see so much.

00:24:01.415 --> 00:24:03.770
And if I have too many widgets
sending updates at

00:24:03.770 --> 00:24:06.187
once, I can't it.

00:24:06.187 --> 00:24:07.830
I'll crash.

00:24:07.830 --> 00:24:13.510
So sending bitmaps through
parcels, through binders--

00:24:13.510 --> 00:24:15.370
it's bad.

00:24:15.370 --> 00:24:16.890
There's a better method
which just uses the

00:24:16.890 --> 00:24:19.270
imaging site image URI.

00:24:19.270 --> 00:24:22.020
So this means that your binder
overhead is really small.

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:25.050
You're just making it URI,
then sending that over.

00:24:25.050 --> 00:24:26.300
Then the launcher
itself loads it.

00:24:29.820 --> 00:24:32.810
There's some tricks to using
this, though, too.

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:34.725
It means you have to have a
URI, so you need a content

00:24:34.725 --> 00:24:36.430
provider for it.

00:24:36.430 --> 00:24:39.260
And previously, I've seen
widgets use the

00:24:39.260 --> 00:24:42.240
file:/sys/ as the URI.

00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:45.285
And this worked, but some future
version of Android is

00:24:45.285 --> 00:24:47.410
going to have to read external
storage permission.

00:24:47.410 --> 00:24:49.152
And the default launcher
doesn't have

00:24:49.152 --> 00:24:49.820
that at this time.

00:24:49.820 --> 00:24:51.630
I kind of doubt it
will get it.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:55.470
So you don't want to be using
this file:/// URI.

00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:58.115
So you need to create your own
kind of wrapper URI that can

00:24:58.115 --> 00:25:02.375
just open up the info stream,
and send it off.

00:25:02.375 --> 00:25:04.405
I don't a good example
of that, as I'm

00:25:04.405 --> 00:25:05.630
not making the widget.

00:25:05.630 --> 00:25:07.050
I'm just receiving it.

00:25:07.050 --> 00:25:10.090
Another downside of the second
[INAUDIBLE] is it's not

00:25:10.090 --> 00:25:14.640
asynchronous, but neither is
the second entry of bitmap.

00:25:14.640 --> 00:25:16.460
This is something that hopefully
a future version of

00:25:16.460 --> 00:25:19.730
Android framework can help
with is letting widgets

00:25:19.730 --> 00:25:20.480
[INAUDIBLE]

00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:22.920
asynchronously, not like
in the launcer.

00:25:22.920 --> 00:25:25.900
And you still want to use small
images here, because

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:28.830
even though you're not creating
a copy of it, but

00:25:28.830 --> 00:25:31.640
you're still getting this
potentially large image to

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:32.230
launch display.

00:25:32.230 --> 00:25:33.800
And so Launcher has
to scale it down.

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:36.210
That's taking time to scale
it, and it's using the

00:25:36.210 --> 00:25:38.430
launcher's memory quicker.

00:25:38.430 --> 00:25:40.260
I've seen some contact widgets,

00:25:40.260 --> 00:25:41.610
scroll the contact widgets.

00:25:41.610 --> 00:25:42.250
So they'll look nice.

00:25:42.250 --> 00:25:43.300
You can fling through
and they scroll.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:44.960
But when you fling through--

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:46.340
[INAUDIBLE]

00:25:46.340 --> 00:25:49.752
and they're loading the full
size contact picture, which

00:25:49.752 --> 00:25:51.710
can be 1,000 pixels wide.

00:25:51.710 --> 00:25:54.984
And you're displaying
it at 96x96.

00:25:54.984 --> 00:25:57.530
So you could scale those ahead
of time, save them to the SD

00:25:57.530 --> 00:25:59.830
card, or save them to your
original storage or something,

00:25:59.830 --> 00:26:02.560
and just give the launcher the
smallest version you need.

00:26:02.560 --> 00:26:03.480
RETO MEIER: That makes
a lot of sense.

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:08.590
I wonder if along the same
lines, using something like--

00:26:08.590 --> 00:26:10.610
I remember exactly the name--
but drawable where you're able

00:26:10.610 --> 00:26:12.990
to set the image level, so
that you have basically,

00:26:12.990 --> 00:26:15.050
rather than having to send
through the bitmap of the

00:26:15.050 --> 00:26:17.920
drawable every time you want to
change it, you could just

00:26:17.920 --> 00:26:20.700
basically send through the int
value of the level that you

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:21.320
want to display.

00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:24.825
Would that sort of approach
work has similarly?

00:26:24.825 --> 00:26:25.940
KEVIN BARRY: Yeah, for
something like--

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:27.960
I imagine [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:29.800
you could use something
like that.

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:33.794
But for something where you're
getting dynamic contents, it's

00:26:33.794 --> 00:26:34.620
not in your resources.

00:26:34.620 --> 00:26:36.100
You're not going to be
able to do that.

00:26:36.100 --> 00:26:38.030
RETO MEIER: That makes
a lot of sense.

00:26:38.030 --> 00:26:40.495
So going on the same lines, you
were mentioning that if

00:26:40.495 --> 00:26:43.710
you get too many updates from
too many widgets at the same

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:46.150
time, then that's going to
cause you problems in

00:26:46.150 --> 00:26:47.720
processing all of those.

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:49.830
And it's something which we've
talked about before, as well,

00:26:49.830 --> 00:26:51.860
which is widgets--

00:26:51.860 --> 00:26:53.770
it's important to keep
them updated.

00:26:53.770 --> 00:26:56.900
But it's also important not
to refresh them too often.

00:26:56.900 --> 00:26:59.320
From your experience, do you
have sort of a best practice

00:26:59.320 --> 00:27:03.010
of what you would recommend as
an appropriate frequency with

00:27:03.010 --> 00:27:05.550
which to refresh your widgets?

00:27:05.550 --> 00:27:08.800
KEVIN BARRY: I guess it really
just happens when it happens.

00:27:08.800 --> 00:27:11.530
Like Nova Launcher actually
tries-- if you're scrolling

00:27:11.530 --> 00:27:13.655
through the screen, it tries
to kind of defer

00:27:13.655 --> 00:27:14.930
those widget updates.

00:27:14.930 --> 00:27:16.720
But it's tricky to that.

00:27:16.720 --> 00:27:18.140
The framework's really
not built for that.

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:21.590
So it can't always
manage to do so.

00:27:21.590 --> 00:27:24.385
Really, the only real problem
I've had is when people have

00:27:24.385 --> 00:27:27.400
had animated widgets, which
Android does not support

00:27:27.400 --> 00:27:27.830
animated widgets.

00:27:27.830 --> 00:27:28.180
RETO MEIER: No, it doesn't.

00:27:28.180 --> 00:27:31.120
KEVIN BARRY: And any hack to do
it slows the whole system

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:31.385
to a crawl.

00:27:31.385 --> 00:27:32.540
It's really bad.

00:27:32.540 --> 00:27:34.840
Don't do animated widgets.

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:35.220
RETO MEIER: Absolutely.

00:27:35.220 --> 00:27:38.130
And it's one of the key tips
that we say is you should

00:27:38.130 --> 00:27:41.310
really only be updating
kind of on demand.

00:27:41.310 --> 00:27:43.800
And certainly no more frequently
than every sort of

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:44.450
30 minutes.

00:27:44.450 --> 00:27:46.840
It's almost like you want to
send as much content to a

00:27:46.840 --> 00:27:51.550
widget as you can, and have it
use things like image pages to

00:27:51.550 --> 00:27:54.270
modify the content without
having to sort of send stuff

00:27:54.270 --> 00:27:57.910
to it to constantly
have to process.

00:27:57.910 --> 00:28:02.820
So I wonder, efficiency aside,
are there certain things which

00:28:02.820 --> 00:28:04.260
you are seeing a lot of people
making mistakes on.

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:07.260
Things causing crashes in
widgets, which you then have

00:28:07.260 --> 00:28:10.140
to deal with within
your launcher?

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:11.650
KEVIN BARRY: So widgets
can crash--

00:28:11.650 --> 00:28:14.230
can and do crash the launcher.

00:28:14.230 --> 00:28:19.030
So Nova Launcher tries to catch
these, and just crash

00:28:19.030 --> 00:28:20.270
the widget, not the
whole thing.

00:28:20.270 --> 00:28:22.410
But then I save the crash
report, so I can try to

00:28:22.410 --> 00:28:24.270
contact widget developers.

00:28:24.270 --> 00:28:25.330
But I can't tell [INAUDIBLE].

00:28:25.330 --> 00:28:27.690
So some common things are--

00:28:27.690 --> 00:28:30.730
there's a legal state exception
that can happen if

00:28:30.730 --> 00:28:33.830
you update a list view
adapter not from

00:28:33.830 --> 00:28:35.480
the UI thread without--

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:36.970
and this can happen
to any of us, too.

00:28:36.970 --> 00:28:39.800
But it happens widgets, too.

00:28:39.800 --> 00:28:42.360
So when you're updating the
adapter used for your

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:45.160
scrollable widget, make sure
you've found the best

00:28:45.160 --> 00:28:46.150
practices there.

00:28:46.150 --> 00:28:48.360
You're updating it from the
UI thread on your--

00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:51.050
you want to find any changes.

00:28:51.050 --> 00:28:53.540
There's transaction too large
which I kind of touched about

00:28:53.540 --> 00:28:55.480
before, which is, generally,
bitmaps.

00:28:55.480 --> 00:28:58.400
But no matter what you're doing,
don't embed a huge

00:28:58.400 --> 00:29:00.560
amount of information in
your widget update.

00:29:00.560 --> 00:29:04.490
Try to get it from a content
provider if you can.

00:29:04.490 --> 00:29:07.320
Oddly enough, there's security
exceptions sometimes.

00:29:07.320 --> 00:29:11.830
Sometimes widgets will ask the
launcher to splice them from a

00:29:11.830 --> 00:29:13.010
content provider it doesn't
have access to.

00:29:13.010 --> 00:29:17.330
Like getting something from a
context provider or whatever.

00:29:17.330 --> 00:29:19.050
I imagine these are caught
pretty quickly.

00:29:19.050 --> 00:29:22.480
But some like the LG launcher
does have more permissions.

00:29:22.480 --> 00:29:24.450
It has permissions to the
context provider.

00:29:24.450 --> 00:29:27.265
So if you just test on some
skinned phone, you're not

00:29:27.265 --> 00:29:28.470
necessarily going to see this.

00:29:28.470 --> 00:29:30.060
So you really want to test
on a third-party

00:29:30.060 --> 00:29:31.000
launcher, as well.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:31.490
RETO MEIER: Yeah.

00:29:31.490 --> 00:29:33.260
And that's a good point,
as well, right?

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:36.990
In that the widgets themselves
are running within your--

00:29:36.990 --> 00:29:40.080
or the launchers process,
which means that the

00:29:40.080 --> 00:29:43.330
permissions which your app
needs, or what your widget

00:29:43.330 --> 00:29:46.390
needs, it depends on what the
home screen, the launcher

00:29:46.390 --> 00:29:49.000
actually has.

00:29:49.000 --> 00:29:51.250
KEVIN BARRY: And you can't--

00:29:51.250 --> 00:29:52.620
no launcher actually does--

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:54.840
it is a [INAUDIBLE] for an SD
card, because I use it for

00:29:54.840 --> 00:29:55.980
other things.

00:29:55.980 --> 00:29:58.230
You can't count on a launcher
having that.

00:29:58.230 --> 00:30:00.970
The default Android
launcher doesn't.

00:30:00.970 --> 00:30:03.530
Well, it does now, because
Android allows anything to it.

00:30:03.530 --> 00:30:07.430
But when Android doesn't, the
Android-- the default launcher

00:30:07.430 --> 00:30:09.900
probably won't.

00:30:09.900 --> 00:30:12.730
And the different launchers
behave different.

00:30:12.730 --> 00:30:14.780
This is different from
the widget crashing.

00:30:14.780 --> 00:30:18.430
But on the Galaxy S III,
the default launcher--

00:30:18.430 --> 00:30:19.440
Samsung's launcher--

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:22.430
doesn't apply any padding
to the widgets.

00:30:22.430 --> 00:30:25.680
But Ice Cream Sandwich said
that widgets get--

00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:28.090
it's generally 80
dp of padding.

00:30:28.090 --> 00:30:31.370
So if you test your widget in
the Samsung launcher, then you

00:30:31.370 --> 00:30:33.740
test it in a third-party
launcher, or you test it in

00:30:33.740 --> 00:30:36.410
the stock Android launcher,
you're going to see the

00:30:36.410 --> 00:30:37.736
padding's different.

00:30:37.736 --> 00:30:40.230
And there's not-- you can't
really control this.

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:42.280
You can't detect if you're
running on Samsung, you can

00:30:42.280 --> 00:30:44.225
add extra padding, because
they might be using a

00:30:44.225 --> 00:30:45.290
third-party launcher.

00:30:45.290 --> 00:30:49.350
So just test so it looks good
either with the padding stock

00:30:49.350 --> 00:30:51.310
Android has, or without
structure

00:30:51.310 --> 00:30:53.050
which it doesn't have.

00:30:53.050 --> 00:30:54.080
RETO MEIER: Yeah, that's
a really good point

00:30:54.080 --> 00:30:55.770
for testing, as well.

00:30:55.770 --> 00:30:56.700
Sorry, I interrupted.

00:30:56.700 --> 00:30:58.110
Go on.

00:30:58.110 --> 00:30:58.830
KEVIN BARRY: Sure.

00:30:58.830 --> 00:31:03.085
One more exception I wanted to
point out was when you're

00:31:03.085 --> 00:31:05.790
dealing with a list view, and
you have different view types.

00:31:05.790 --> 00:31:08.130
So this is sometimes you have a
header, and then you have an

00:31:08.130 --> 00:31:09.760
actually item.

00:31:09.760 --> 00:31:12.950
You have to return a count
for get view type count.

00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:15.750
And so in a normal app, if you
don't return the correct value

00:31:15.750 --> 00:31:17.160
here while you're scrolling
through it,

00:31:17.160 --> 00:31:18.750
your app will crash.

00:31:18.750 --> 00:31:22.193
In the case of widgets, if you
return the wrong get view type

00:31:22.193 --> 00:31:25.632
count, then the launcher itself
is going to crash.

00:31:25.632 --> 00:31:25.990
RETO MEIER: Fun times.

00:31:25.990 --> 00:31:27.610
KEVIN BARRY: And you'll see in
the right index out of balance

00:31:27.610 --> 00:31:31.560
exception, add scrap view--
that's the key there.

00:31:31.560 --> 00:31:34.980
So there's fixes to probably
increase your get view type

00:31:34.980 --> 00:31:36.690
count to the correct number.

00:31:36.690 --> 00:31:38.650
RETO MEIER: Right, and
that's a good tip.

00:31:38.650 --> 00:31:40.230
That's actually a good point
you made earlier, as well,

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:40.950
about testing.

00:31:40.950 --> 00:31:43.660
I think a lot of people are
going to just use an emulator,

00:31:43.660 --> 00:31:45.920
or whichever device they happen
to own, to test their

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:49.260
widgets, not considering the
fact that not only are you

00:31:49.260 --> 00:31:51.030
going to have different home
screens from different

00:31:51.030 --> 00:31:52.610
manufacturers.

00:31:52.610 --> 00:31:54.660
But in fact, users may download
things like Nova

00:31:54.660 --> 00:31:58.470
Launcher to have their own
third-party launcher.

00:31:58.470 --> 00:32:00.930
So I think it's a good tip for
people building widgets to

00:32:00.930 --> 00:32:04.570
test on multiple launcher
implementations to make sure

